# Back up to Git after every modification

Treat **commit + push to `origin`** as the default way to finish any change (backup to GitHub). Human-oriented steps also live in `AEP Profile/BACKUP-TO-GITHUB.md`.

Whenever you complete a task that modifies project files (code, HTML/CSS/JS, server, config, docs the user asked to change):

1. Run `git status` and review what changed.
2. Stage the relevant paths (`git add …`). Prefer focused commits; if the user’s request touched one area, avoid bundling unrelated dirty files unless they share one logical change.
3. Commit with a **clear, imperative subject** and optional body (what changed and why, in plain language).
4. Run **`git push origin main`** (or the current branch) after the commit so the remote stays backed up—**unless** the user explicitly asked for a local commit only, or push fails (e.g. network); if push fails, say so and what to run when online.

Do not leave completed work uncommitted when wrapping up a change. If there is nothing to commit after verification, say so briefly.
